  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Because of the cost of the journey, William Lloyd Garrison believes it is better to send a letter to be read at the &quot;rescue&quot; anniversary than to be present. He exults in the success of the Woman&apos;s Rights Convention in Syracuse. The press has been respectful. Garrison comments: &quot;What a change, my dear friend, has been wrought since 1840, when the American Anti-Slavery Society was rent asunder, on the sole ground (at least ostensibly) that it was an intolerable outrage, and shockingly unscriptural, to place a woman on one of its committees!&quot; The Grimke sisters are staying at Samuel Philbrick&apos;s house in Brookline. Angelina is ill with a fever. The seceding portion of the Liberty Party, headed by William Goodell, will reassemble in Syracuse. Garrison calls the nomination of William Goodell for the presidency of the United States a farce. Gerrit Smith is still a greenhorn politically.</subfield>
